<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/technology <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/technology" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 11 日星期五 20:10:56 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The AI Nanny in Your Baby’s Future]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>先进的人工智能助手将减轻父母的负担，并为婴儿和幼儿提供他们所需的来回刺激。但会不会有开发成本呢？ <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826784/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·加兰<span>保罗·加兰</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001034485"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001034485"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">达纳·苏斯金德</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 10:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-nanny-in-your-babys-future-999d0e50"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>想象一下十年后成为婴儿或幼儿的父母。育儿的大部分方面都不会改变，但其他方面很可能会因人工智能的使用而发生改变。人工智能设备很可能成为电子保姆，就像前几代父母采用电视和视频游戏作为减轻看护职责的工具一样。</p><p>人工智能泰迪熊可以以个性化的方式回应婴儿的咕咕声和幼儿的问题。电脑辅助的“保姆”永远不会厌倦一遍又一遍地阅读同一本书，这会让睡觉变得轻而易举。高级婴儿版 Alexa 可以根据需要唱歌和教授喜爱的歌曲、玩游戏，甚至推断婴儿哭泣的原因。</p><p>与上一代的创新一样，这些工具将利用技术来吸引孩子们的注意力，并节省父母的时间和压力。然而，与以前的工具不同的是，我们有理由担心，由于人工智能儿童保育设备在模仿人类行为方面非常复杂，它们可能会改变婴儿和幼儿处理他们的世界经历的方式。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span>向年轻的大脑引入响应式人工智能可能会以我们无法预料的根本方式改变他们。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>这是因为我们的大脑<a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326690391_Why_Early_Intervention_is_Important_Neuroplasticity_in_Early_Childhood" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">在生命的最初几年中</a>以非凡的方式发育。人类婴儿来到这个世界时还没有完全成熟。一个可能的进化原因是，如果一个典型的胎儿在子宫内发育的时间更长，它的头部就会太大而无法安全分娩。因此大自然不得不妥协：婴儿在 40 周后出生，但 40 周大的婴儿大脑仍有大量发育空间需要完成。大部分成长发生在生命的头两年，速度惊人。每秒大约形成一百万个新的神经连接。到孩子三岁生日时，大脑发育到成人大小的 80% 左右。</p><p>这提供了一个很短的时间窗口，可以通过培养孩子的大脑基础发育来帮助他们走向人生的成功。这是为什么人类是所有物种中最聪明、最具创造力和生产力的核心。</p><p>婴儿最需要优化这个快速进步的早期阶段的是<a href="https://news.mit.edu/2018/conversation-boost-childrens-brain-response-language-0214" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">丰富的对话</a>，发展心理学家称之为“服务和回报”互动。这对于父母与孩子的互动来说是很自然的事情，并且众所周知可以促进孩子认知和情感技能的成长。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="515" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831743?width=700&amp;height=515" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">电视的出现引起了人们对电视对儿童影响的担忧，但它不具备人工智能的互动能力。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：哈罗德·M·兰伯特/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在此之前，这种必要的成分只能由有爱心的成年人提供。不管营销人员如何让你相信，古典音乐、教育电视和小爱因斯坦视频<a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0022347607004477?casa_token=f_qXEPK71FUAAAAA:DA5F_uthkXR64mKQd3_fjkWu7ucq47ZuUOQcZQWO90KBddX94dXRZUjF2HvGUhLbg9s7_LFz" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">不能在婴儿的大脑中建立有意义的新神经连接</a>。他们的反应不是偶然的——没有来回。</p><p>新兴的人工智能工具改变了这一切。它们是按照我们的形象构建的，就像人类大脑的构建方式一样。它们由复杂连接的神经网络组成，由大量数据输入形成。 ChatGPT 以大型语言模型的形式接收必要的输入，而儿童以与成人的爱互动的形式接收它。当我们用自动化的替代方案来补充大脑构建的人类互动时，这条界限就会变得模糊。</p><p>不难理解为什么父母希望利用技术创新来减轻家庭负担。抚养孩子，尤其是幼儿时期，是一项耗费全身心力的任务。对于不知所措的父母来说，人工智能的帮助可能会带来变革，就像洗衣机和其他电器在上世纪中叶彻底改变了护理方式一样，让女性大量进入劳动力市场。</p><p>为什么不使用人工智能保姆让人类婴儿参与到构建大脑的来回对话中呢？它可能会对发展产生深远的积极影响，在儿童大脑最具“可塑性”（即最有能力根据所遇到的情况重新布线）的时期，增加大脑构建时刻的频率和一致性。这项技术可能会给那些可能会出现发育迟缓的儿童带来福音。它可以帮助释放认知潜力并缩小成就差距。</p><p>但我们必须谨慎行事。新技术可以塑造我们大脑的结构。当早期人类开始使用工具来制作标记和图案时，新的神经元被激活，最终使大脑能够以全新的方式使用视觉皮层——阅读和书写。在我们这个时代，《美国医学会儿科杂志》一月份的一份报告表明，习惯性使用社交媒体正在改变青少年大脑对社会奖励的反应。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831756?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">由人工智能驱动的家庭助理已经开始与孩子们进行对话交流。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Koh Sze Kiat/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>关于大脑的基础发育，我们还有很多不了解的地方。让年轻的大脑接触响应式人工智能可能会以我们无法预料的根本方式改变他们。如果我们提供错误的输入或互动方式，我们可能会以深远的方式扭曲认知发展。</p><p>考虑一下神经科学领域最近的一项发现。研究人员早就知道，成人和儿童之间的更多对话可以促进儿童语言和词汇发展的进步。但过去十年的研究揭示了这种关系背后的一个关键机制：当儿童和他们的人类照顾者试图一起交流或玩耍时，他们的脑电波实际上是同步的。在成年人进行协作活动（例如集体唱歌或跳舞以及面对面交流）时也观察到了这一点。他们在相同的大脑区域经历相似的大脑活动，并且他们的脑电波越匹配，结果就越有成效。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>你能想象使用人工智能设备来照顾你的孩子吗？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>普林斯顿大学的一组研究人员<a href="https://www.princeton.edu/news/2020/01/09/baby-and-adult-brains-sync-during-play-finds-princeton-baby-lab" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">在 2020 年报告</a>称，这种现象尤其发生在儿童及其照顾者的前额叶皮层中，而学习是在前额叶皮层中进行的。对幼儿的进一步研究表明，这种“神经同步”可以促进词汇习得以及<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9791495/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">社交学习</a>和解决问题的能力。人工智能虽然能够进行来回交换，但缺乏神经同步所需的物理人脑。我们根本不知道对正在发育的人类大脑来说，体验其中一种而没有另一种意味着什么。</p><p>对于终生成就而言，韧性与认知同样重要，是另一种几乎完全依赖于早期基础大脑发育的技能。当孩子在生命早期遇到各种经历并在<a href="https://developingchild.harvard.edu/science/key-concepts/resilience/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">有爱心的成人</a>的引导下经历这些经历时，他们就会学会如何适应性地做出反应。</p><p> <a href="https://center-for-attachment.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Levy-Steele-2011-Grit-copy.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">研究还表明</a>，对从父母那里得到大量照顾有积极记忆的成年人表现出更高水平的“勇气”和野心。但如果父母放弃一些基本责任，孩子对机器人产生依恋意味着什么呢？谢菲尔德大学研究人员诺埃尔·夏基 (Noel Sharkey) 和阿曼达·夏基 (Amanda Sharkey) 在 2021 年《道德与信息技术》杂志上发表的一篇<a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10676-020-09573-9" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">论文</a>中写道：“这可能会对他们的社交和情感发展产生严重影响。”</p><p>我们不能也不应该把人工智能精灵放回瓶子里。但如果没有更好的理解，我们就有可能浪费生命最初几年的发展能力，并有可能破坏我们自己的进化结构。</p><p> <em>Dana Suskind 博士是 TMW 早期学习 + 公共卫生中心的联合主任，也是芝加哥大学儿科人工耳蜗项目的创始主任。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/6848d7bc-2ce5-4441-989b-37ffca2218b2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 14:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-nanny-in-your-babys-future-999d0e50</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ai-nanny-in-your-babys-future-999d0e50<category>华尔街日报评论</category><category>技术</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>生物学</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>寄养/收养</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>为人父母/为人父母</category><category>心理学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>社会问题</category><category>福利/社会服务</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>生物学</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>养育</category><category>采用</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>养育子女</category><category>为人父母</category><category>心理学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>社会问题</category><category>福利</category><category>社会服务</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Startups Are Dying, and Venture Investors Aren’t Saving Them]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>投资者变得更加挑剔，威胁到数百家在最近的繁荣时期筹集资金的初创公司<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833621/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供； iStock<span>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供；股票</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125884"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125884"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/berber-jin" itemprop="url" rel="author">柏柏尔·金</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 8:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/startups-are-dying-amid-drought-in-venture-funding-a9005ad2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>一年半前，马特·雷德勒 (Matt Redler) 签署了一项协议，为他的支付初创公司 Panther 筹集 2000 万美元。他制定了雄心勃勃的计划，以吸引更多客户并将收入增加一倍以上。</p><p>他表示，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯入侵乌克兰</a>扰乱金融市场后，他的投资者纷纷撤资。雷德勒改变了他的商业模式，帮助公司雇用承包商而不是全职工人，以减少现金消耗。接下来的一年里，他向 50 多名投资者进行了推介，但没有找到任何主要支持者。六月，他决定关闭 Panther，避免破产的可能性。</p><p>在历史性的风险投资荒中， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/more-startups-throw-in-the-towel-unable-to-raise-money-for-their-ideas-eff8305b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">初创公司正在消亡</a>，这表明，尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-08-11-2023?mod=livemarkets-ribbon&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">科技股反弹</a>， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-mania-triggers-dot-com-bubble-flashbacks-7848d402?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">投资者对人工智能</a>着迷，但硅谷不可或缺的引擎却正在遭受痛苦。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832719?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>长期以来，大多数初创公司都无法进入成年期，但在过去十年的大部分时间里，在资本过剩和低利率的情况下，他们往往可以依靠几轮融资来继续尝试。现在，在最近的创业热潮顶峰或接近顶峰成立的初创企业正在认识到，随着投资者缩减支出，维持生存并不那么容易。</p><p> Everywhere Ventures 的执行合伙人珍妮·菲尔丁 (Jenny Fielding) 表示：“没有人愿意为那些正在蓬勃发展的企业提供资金，而这些企业却能够在繁荣时期继续发展。” “在接下来的 12 个月里，我们将看到更多的公司倒闭。”</p><p>风险投资家表示，他们正在避免为缺乏明显收入增长迹象或盈利途径的企业提供资金。更高的门槛导致融资大幅减少：根据 PitchBook 的数据，截至 6 月 30 日的一年中，美国科技初创企业的投资下降了 49%。</p><p>数据显示，第二季度投资者还将对美国早期初创企业的资金削减了约一半，至 100 亿美元。鉴于这种资金来源对于启动年轻企业并帮助它们成长至关重要，这种撤退加速了新初创企业关闭的浪潮。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E8DCC2B0-F066-41EA-9053-96EC3A35B05E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fstartups-are-dying-amid-drought-in-venture-funding-a9005ad2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">芯片制造商英伟达跻身市值 1 万亿美元的公司专属俱乐部。 《华尔街日报》的 Asa Fitch 详细分析了 Nvidia 是如何实现这一目标的，以及人工智能为何推动该公司快速增长。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>虽然初创公司的失败很难追踪，但近几个月来，源源不断的风险投资支持的公司已经关闭或缩小了业务规模。</p><p>支付处理商 Plastiq 在与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-flock-to-spacs-where-risks-lurk-and-track-records-are-poor-11605263402?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一家特殊目的收购公司的</a>合并失败后于 5 月申请破产。生物技术初创公司 Goldfinch Bio 在未能筹集更多资金后于今年早些时候倒闭。 Buzzer 是一个移动体育平台，从迈克尔乔丹等名人那里筹集了 2000 万美元，但由于市场动态，该平台于 6 月关闭。 Poparazzi 是一款由风险投资公司 Benchmark 支持的照片共享应用程序，曾一度登上 App Store 榜首，但也被关闭了。</p><p> Hopin 是一家热闹的虚拟活动初创公司，在不到一年的时间里筹集了近 10 亿美元，最近以 1500 万美元的价格出售了其主要业务，但根据一份财务文件，如果达到业绩目标，它可能会获得最多 3500 万美元的收益。</p><p>此次出售仅占 Hopin 在疫情期间获得的超过 70 亿美元估值的一小部分。知情人士称，该公司曾受到安德森·霍洛维茨(Andreessen Horowitz)等行业巨头的青睐，现在也将其筹集的大部分现金返还给投资者。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>在市场转向之前，Panther 的 Redler 能够以 6000 万美元的估值从投资者那里筹集到现金。去年，他甚至很难以 1000 万美元的降价获得利息，因为投资者越来越不愿意在充满竞争对手的行业中冒险投资一家年轻的、未经证实的公司。</p><p>风险投资公司 Root Ventures 的普通合伙人李·爱德华兹 (Lee Edwards) 表示：“投资者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-business-plan-no-problem-chatgpt-spawns-an-investor-gold-rush-in-ai-6bdbed3c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">仍然会关注</a>一个团队和一个梦想，但这种情况比以前少了一些。”</p><p>去年，软件开发初创公司 Toolchain 开始向投资者推销 A 轮融资——通常是称为种子轮的初始融资后的第一笔融资。该公司已经筹集了 600 万美元，正在与开发商签约进入其平台，并计划利用新资金进行销售和营销闪电战。</p><p> Toolchain 首席执行官本吉·温伯格 (Benjy Weinberger) 此后遭到 60 多名投资者的拒绝。温伯格说，他们告诉他，该公司的收入增长速度不够快，不足以证明新资金的合理性<strong>。</strong>他说，去年科技行业<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cutting-costs-not-jobs-is-focus-for-many-cfos-facing-slowdown-11670630790?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更广泛的成本削减</a>导致了潜在客户取消销售会议，从而损害了该业务。工具链于今年夏天关闭。</p><p>温伯格认为，当投资者更愿意根据用户增长等指标对初创公司进行风险更高的押注时，他的初创公司可能能够在更加看涨的市场中筹集现金。 “肯定有时机不对的因素，”他说。</p><p> Toolchain 早期投资者 Hunter Walk 表示，随着市场的变化，投资者希望看到美元超过用户的证据<strong>&nbsp;</strong>牵引力，导致公司融资困难。他表示，去年初结束的投资热潮已经让越来越多的初创公司因融资前景黯淡而倒闭。</p><p>他说：“我们现在面临的是一场完美风暴，导致比平常更多的停工。”</p><p>各轮融资通常为初创公司提供了至少两年的运行空间，这意味着一些在 2021 年最后筹集资金的公司可能很快就会耗尽现金。初创公司通常会选择在银行账户耗尽前几个月结束业务，以确保有足够的资金来补偿客户、员工和投资者。</p><p>此类关闭更多<strong>&nbsp;</strong>两年前这种情况很少见，当时大量资金涌入风险投资公司，导致它们为投机性商业想法提供资金，但长期成功的前景微乎其微。鉴于筹集新资金的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venture-fundraising-hits-nine-year-low-c2b4774?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">难度</a>，初创企业的低迷迫使这些公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venture-firms-scale-back-megafunds-in-strategy-shift-17807564?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">缩减</a>雄心并更加谨慎地投资。</p><p>如今，“要想获得 A 轮融资，你需要大量的收入，”Root Ventures 的投资者爱德华兹说。 “风险投资家正在回归基本面。”</p><p> Panther 创始人雷德勒表示，他的支付初创公司在一年多的时间里一直处于生存模式，最后才做出关闭的决定。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对今年剩余时间里的硅谷有何展望？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Panther 成立于 2020 年，是一群年轻的支付初创公司的一部分，旨在帮助公司处理海外招聘的后勤复杂性。与繁荣时期的许多其他初创公司一样，Panther 专注于增长而非盈利。该公司利用筹集到的 650 万美元聘请了一批工程师和法律合作伙伴来构建和扩展其产品，这种模式导致了大量现金消耗。</p><p>去年年初，该轮融资失败后，Panther 解雇了部分员工，转而采用成本较低的模式来帮助公司雇用承包商。这一变化迫使这家初创公司从头开始重建业务，年收入损失约 100 万美元。</p><p>一年多来，当雷德勒试图寻找另一位大支持者时，该公司仅靠少量小额支票维持生存。雷德勒表示，随着现金紧张，他将自己的工资削减了 38%。</p><p>去年 12 月，情况变得如此严峻，雷德勒和他的联合创始人考虑申请贷款，并由他们个人担保以维持业务的运转。鉴于黑豹仍在烧钱，他们的申请被拒绝，这使得贷款看起来有风险。六月份他终于放弃了生意。</p><p> “我吃了几个月的玻璃，时间太长了，”雷德勒说。</p><p>写信给 Berber Jin，邮箱为<a href="mailto:berber.jin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">berber.jin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/startups-are-dying-amid-drought-in-venture-funding-a9005ad2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/startups-are-dying-amid-drought-in-venture-funding-a9005ad2<author><![CDATA[Berber Jin]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>企业融资</category><category>融资协议</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>私募股权/风险投资</category><category>系列/轮融资</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>企业融资</category><category>融资协议</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>私人产权</category><category>风险投资</category><category>系列</category><category>轮融资</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Here’s What a $5 Million Retirement Looks Like in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>退休人员公开他们的财务生活以及他们如何度过时间和金钱<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832718/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》<span>丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/veronica-dagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">维罗妮卡·达格尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>多少钱都无法让退休后无忧无虑，但 500 万美元可能就差不多了。</p><p>很少有美国人能够在 401(k) 计划和个人退休账户中存下接近这一金额的钱。根据<a href="https://www.ebri.org/" target="_blank" class="icon none">员工福利研究所</a>使用 2019 年消费者财务调查对退休账户进行的分析，500 万美元的退休储蓄金使您跻身前 0.1% 的家庭之列。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1092" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d663f044-8f28-4ec7-8377-2302a6c566d6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>为了了解 500 万美元可以在退休后购买什么，我们采访了全国各地拥有该金额储蓄的退休人员。</p><p>大多数人从未想过会成为百万富翁，但从职业生涯的早期就勤于储蓄。</p><p>尽管与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-under-1-million-america-846a6ab6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">我们介绍的许多退休人员</a>相比，他们不太担心自己的钱花光了，但他们并不都过着奢侈的生活。有些人已经很多年没有买新衣服了。其他人继续兼职工作。</p><p>他们在环球旅行上挥霍无度，但像大多数年长的美国人一样，担心自己的健康和家人。</p><p>仅靠金钱也无法解决退休人员面临的另一个问题：如何在人生的这一章中找到目的和意义？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>保罗·谢姆韦尔 (Paul Shemwell) 在驾驶商用飞机和喷气式战斗机四十年后于 12 月退休。</p><p>尽管这位 65 岁的老人感觉自己的财务状况很安全，已经攒下了约 610 万美元，但他还没有制定接下来的飞行计划。</p><p>对于这位前飞行员来说，这种随意的态度是一个巨大的改变，他在空军的 13 年中磨练了自己的战略思维能力。他的服役经历也教会他仔细权衡自己的选择，这一理念指导着他的退休生活。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2decacce-5119-4fbc-9b6f-3b2bd857ad6d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LUV" class="">西南航空公司</a>工作 28 年后，他不再乘坐飞机<span class="company-name-type">，</span>但旅行仍然是他的热情所在。他计划今年秋天进行四次旅行，这种旅行癖让他每月花费约 3,000 美元。他每月还要花费大约 9,000 美元用于财产税、房屋和汽车保险等费用。</p><p>他的一天通常从锻炼或网球课开始。作为一名狂热的滑雪爱好者，他已经购买了本赛季的通行证，并计划每年至少进行一次水肺潜水旅行。</p><p>谢姆韦尔拒绝了几份重返驾驶舱的工作机会，部分原因是他不需要钱。</p><p>他计划在达到完全退休年龄后领取<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/social-security-payment-increase-cola-2024-retirement-a3fce38e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">社会保障</a>，这将使年收入增加约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/173863f5-743a-4d58-a219-b57a7e01cbf8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>空巢老人的生活是另一个巨大的变化。他的儿子是大学二年级学生，女儿今年秋天开始上大学。谢姆韦尔已离婚并拥有共同监护权，他表示，他将深入参与孩子的生活作为首要任务。</p><p>他的航班时刻表使他能够灵活地参加孩子们的大部分网球和足球比赛。现在他们都在上学了，他想去看看他们比赛。</p><p>谢姆韦尔现在花更多的时间和他的朋友在一起，大多数工作日都会和他们一起吃午餐。</p><p>他不是一个活跃的交易者，但仍关注市场。他的投资组合<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/it-isnt-just-boomers-lots-of-older-americans-are-stock-obsessed-ca069e1a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">95%是股票</a>，大部分是指数基金，还有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a>等少数个股<span class="company-name-type">。</span> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832732?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">保罗·谢姆韦尔最近再次开始打网球。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的杰克·汤普森</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他的父亲已经 90 多岁了，所以谢姆韦尔并不担心他大量的股票配置。</p><p> “我的计划是继续量入为出或量入为出，保持投资并为我的孩子们留下一些东西，”他说。</p><p>谢姆韦尔在休斯顿的房屋抵押贷款还剩大约 30 万美元。他的再融资利率为 2.99%，因此他并不急于偿还债务。</p><p>他驾驶的是一辆 2016 款英菲尼迪，行驶里程约为 80,000 英里。这辆车以及他为女儿购买的二手奔驰都是付费的。他每月全额支付信用卡账单。</p><p> “我喜欢让事情变得简单，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Jay Myer 积累了足够的积蓄，可以在 2020 年提前退休，因为他在 401(k) 计划中缴纳了数十年的最高缴款。</p><p> 25 岁时，迈尔读了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vanguards-founder-a-force-of-nature-11547812685?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">先锋创始人约翰·博格尔 (John Bogle)</a>写的一本支持低成本指数基金的书。他也按照著名选股家彼得·林奇的建议购买了个股，“买你所知道的”。对于现年 61 岁的迈尔来说，这意味着科技股和与他进行软件交易的公司的股票，其中包括家得<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HD" class="">宝 (Home Depot)</a> <span class="company-name-type">，</span>他在几十年前以每股 3 美元的分割调整价格购买了该公司。</p><p> “我当时还很年轻，才读到有关退休的文章，但这对我来说很有意义。如果你降低投资成本，你就会保留更多的利润，”迈尔说，他的退休账户投资于七支先锋指数基金。</p><p>他和 60 岁的妻子安妮塔 (Anita) 开着二手车，并严格遵守预算，以便 Myer 从 22 岁起就可以向他的 401(k) 账户缴纳最高年度限额。安妮塔 (Anita) 一直担任牙科保健员，直到 2000 年他们的第二个儿子出生。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d872ec8a-8e9f-4719-9763-3d49c3645f1b.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>迈尔说，他决定提前退休的部分原因是他的继父是一位小企业主，喜欢旅行和与孙辈共度时光。</p><p> “他向我展示了你可以放下工作场所并重新认识自己，”迈尔说。</p><p>起初，失去稳定的薪水是很可怕的。当 2020 年市场暴跌时，他仔细检查了这对夫妇的每一次购买，甚至餐巾纸，但很快意识到，考虑到他们的健康储蓄，这样做是没有必要的。</p><p>这对夫妇现在拥有 420 万美元，一半在退休账户，一半在应税账户。</p><p>这对夫妇利用最近出售亚特兰大房屋的收益，以 925,000 美元在卡里购买了一套房子，距离他们经常见到的大儿子的家人有 2 英里。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832750?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迈尔斯夫妇喜欢烹饪、园艺和旅行，并计划改进他们的新家。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Kate Medley</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他们每年花费约 130,000 美元，其中包括 5,000 美元的财产税。他们每个月在食品上花费约 700 美元，在健康保险上花费 1,000 美元。 （由于他们目前用现金储备支出，这对夫妇的应税收入足够低，有资格获得保险补贴。）</p><p>为了最大化他每月的福利，迈尔表示他会等到 70 岁才领取社会保障。</p><p>这对夫妇曾考虑出售一些个股，以将更多资金投入债券，但由于利润所欠的资本利得税而打消了念头。他们决定把最大的赢家留给他们的两个儿子。</p><p>迈尔斯夫妇每年的旅行预算约为 20,000 美元，他们正计划今年去西班牙旅行，他们的小儿子今年就住在那里。</p><p>两人都喜欢烹饪和园艺。迈尔说他很享受自由自在的时间。</p><p> “现在我有了更多的时间，我学会了拥抱无聊，放慢脚步，有时接受读书或骑自行车就足够了，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>对于胡亨利博士来说，工作是实现令人满意的退休生活的一部分。</p><p>这位加利福尼亚州欧文市的外科医生过去每周工作长达 80 个小时，但现在他在假期期间兼职工作。 “我真的很喜欢旅行，”72 岁的胡说。</p><p> Hwu 是一名来自台湾的移民，他说他和已故的妻子于 1979 年来到美国。在芝加哥学习了五年外科手术并于 1986 年在密歇根州完成结直肠外科奖学金后，Hwu 搬到了南加州，他和妻子在那里抚养了三个孩子。</p><p>在达到医疗实践规定的 65 岁强制退休年龄之前，Hwu 开始阅读有关退休的书籍（他说还有《华尔街日报》的文章）。他开始打高尔夫球和泡菜球，还买了一把吉他，重拾了自医学院以来他几乎没有时间从事的一项爱好。</p><p>但 2016 年退休后，他错过了工作并开始接受以前诊所的任务。</p><p>每天早上，他都会问自己这一天要做什么。 “我不喜欢那种感觉，”胡说，他的妻子在他退休后不久就去世了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832859?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Henry Hwu 博士于 2016 年正式退休，但在不旅行时继续兼职工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ryan Young</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>胡每年旅行长达三个月，去台湾看望他 98 岁的母亲，或者游览苏格兰、法国、德国、日本和瑞士，他曾在那里给朋友买了很多巧克力，结果行李箱都坏了。</p><p> Hwu经常带着他的吉他。最近在伦敦时，他给了一位街头音乐家 20 英镑让他让位，以便他可以演奏 Everly Brothers 的《Let It Be Me》。 “我不知道人们是否喜欢它，但有一位观众站在我面前，”胡说。</p><p>胡仍然喜欢参加医学会议和阅读医学期刊。</p><p>在 2017 年的一次会议上，他遇到了洛斯阿拉莫斯一家乡村医院唯一的外科医生 NM Hwu，现在大多数月份都会前往洛斯阿拉莫斯为外科医生接班几天。在那里，他喜欢徒步旅行并拜访在阿尔伯克基担任会计师的儿子。</p><p>在家时，Hwu 会去上吉他课，并经常见到他的女儿和小孙女。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f3b9dd2c-d95e-4677-81b1-f14a149509ca.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>他的房子价值150万美元。他拥有第二套房子，价值 120 万美元，每月租金为 3,500 美元。他每套房子欠约 50 万美元，但并不急于偿还抵押贷款，因为利率低于 3%。</p><p> Hwu 将其退休账户中超过 100 万美元的资金几乎全部投资于股票基金和个股，包括苹果、<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达</a><span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>他每月领取 2,700 美元的社会保障福利，从 65 岁开始领取。他每年领取约 13 万美元的养老金，去年从每日工作中赚取约 30 万美元。</p><p>旅行是他的大手笔，每年花费 10 万美元。其他开支约为每月 4,000 美元，这还不包括他的抵押贷款付款。</p><p>他每年还支付 6,800 美元的长期护理保险。</p><p> “我妈妈活到了 98 岁，我有一天会无法照顾自己，”他说。 “我想减轻孩子们的负担。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在成长过程中，鲍勃·弗雷（Bob Frey）从未想过自己会成为百万富翁退休。</p><p>从西点军校毕业后，他在现役期间获得了硕士学位，然后通过陆军预备役奖学金和退伍军人法案获得了兽医学位。他担任预备役军官 26 年，60 岁退休。他从 30 多岁开始就用尽了退休计划缴款。</p><p>日子有时很艰难，比如当他借了大约 15 万美元开办兽医诊所时。多年来，他卖掉了三项业务，其中包括两家兽医诊所。他说，这些退出极大地增加了他的价值。</p><p>如今，80 岁的鲍勃和 75 岁的妻子帕特·弗雷已经存下了约 610 万美元，其中几乎一半投资于个人退休账户。</p><p>弗雷每年领取 60,000 美元的军事养老金，加上每年约 14,000 美元的退伍军人伤残补偿金，因为他在越南服役后出现了听力损失。这对夫妇从社会保障金中总共领取了约 56,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b82deef5-2fa7-4359-8b0c-802cb8012644.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “我们拥有的钱比我们一生花的还要多，”他说。</p><p>这对夫妇结婚已有 30 多年，育有 5 个成年子女。 20 世纪 90 年代初，他们搬到了蒙大拿州博兹曼，寻求新的开始并更接近大自然。帕特继续她的护理生涯，鲍勃接受重新培训，成为一名认证财务规划师。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您为退休制定了哪些财务计划？请通过下面的表格告诉我们您的经历。</em></p></div></div><p>弗雷家族尽管富有，但通常都会避免其装饰。鲍勃说他已经大约 20 年没有买过新的运动外套了。这对夫妇住在蒙大拿州，他们说他们不太用得着正装，宁愿穿着牛仔裤和运动鞋到处走动。帕特经常和朋友一起去大自然散步。</p><p>弗雷夫妇预计将花费约 150 万美元来帮助支付他们九个孙辈的教育费用。他们每年还向他们最喜欢的慈善机构（包括他们的教堂）捐赠大约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832798?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">鲍勃·弗雷 (Bob Frey) 在世界各地和离家不远的加拉廷河 (Gallatin River) 飞钓。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rebecca Stumpf for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这对夫妇没有债务，也没有过多调整他们的投资，其中大约 70% 投资于股票基金。鲍勃说，他们死后可能会向慈善机构留下约 100 万美元。</p><p>弗雷夫妇也很重视旅行，每年会拨出约 35,000 美元用于环游世界。他们曾五次访问新西兰，鲍勃经常将他对飞钓的热爱与阿拉斯加、墨西哥和南美洲的旅行结合起来。</p><p>他们还喜欢与朋友单独旅行。帕特经常与朋友一起前往欧洲和加拉帕戈斯群岛。她跳过了鲍勃的狩猎之旅。</p><p> “我不想睡在帐篷里，把麋鹿带出树林，”她说。</p><p>写信给 Veronica Dagher <a href="mailto:Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com）</a>和 Anne Tergesen（ <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com）</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2d22c5e9-a490-4c14-9b85-792395763a6e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/89ceea19-a743-45d2-8530-c974dc040b2e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9<author><![CDATA[Veronica DagherAnne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Amazon Wants to Deliver Your Order Without a Box]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这家零售巨头正在减少数百万件货物的包装<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832983/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="亚马逊可以减少包装，部分原因是它已经建立了自己的配送网络，包括像纽约州梅尔维尔这样的配送中心，以减少包裹到达最终目的地所需的距离。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>亚马逊可以减少包装，部分原因是它已经建立了自己的配送网络，包括像纽约梅尔维尔这样的配送中心，以减少包裹到达最终目的地所需的距离。约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻<span>约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124909"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sebastian-herrera" itemprop="url" rel="author">塞巴斯蒂安·埃雷拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>数以百万计的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">亚马逊</a>订单在没有任何额外包装的情况下到达美国各地的家门口。门口制造商的盒子里可能有一台新电视。搅拌机看起来就像是从商店货架上取下来的。一盒婴儿湿巾或垃圾袋也是如此。</p><p>这一变化代表了这家科技巨头对其交付流程进行彻底改革的下一个前沿，首席执行官安迪·贾西(Andy Jassy)希望此举能够吸引那些因每周收到和丢弃的亚马逊品牌盒子数量而推迟的顾客。</p><p>该公司去年改造了其物流网络，实现了更快、更高效的交付。对于公司保持主导地位、降低成本和实现与气候影响相关的目标来说，消除或减少包装变得越来越重要。</p><p>亚马逊去年聘请帕特·林德纳（Pat Lindner）担任包装和创新第一副总裁，他说：“许多高级领导都认识到这一点变得越来越重要。” “我们公司迫切需要在包装创新方面迈出下一步。”</p><p>亚马逊表示，该公司交付的大约 11% 的商品现在到达时没有额外的包装，或者该公司所说的“用自己的集装箱运输”。顾客通常可以在结帐时选择是否需要额外包装或更喜欢没有包装的订单。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832954?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">亚马逊在其位于华盛顿州萨姆纳的测试设施中测试包裹是否能够在运送过程中毫发无伤。高级实验室技术员雷特·布鲁斯 (Rett Bruce) 解释说，该压缩测试仪模拟垂直压缩中的堆叠。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的科鲁德开斋节</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>挑战范围从实际到情感。亚马逊需要帮助其供应商创造出足够坚固的包装，以便能够自行运输，同时又不会添加额外的材料来削弱其废除包装的整体目的。例如，它需要确定顾客是否不希望将一大包卫生纸放在家门口，让所有邻居看到。</p><p>亚马逊正在利用其对包装商品公司和其他供应商的强大影响力以及激励措施，促使他们改进包装以在运输中生存。例如，网站上的供应商可以获得消除额外包装层的激励。</p><p> While Amazon is losing some branding power from cutting back on its signature brown boxes, it is betting that the elimination of extra packaging will create goodwill with its customers, many of whom, it said, have asked the company for such changes.</p><p> “Sometimes you get a giant box with a very little item that, quite frankly, wasn&#39;t breakable in the first place. And you wonder why they used all that material,” said Kenneth Levine, a 76-year-old in River Vale, NJ, who said he receives Amazon packages about once a week. He has yet to notice the option to reduce packaging at checkout, but said he would be open to it for reasonable and non-fragile items, like books. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C72EA178-F0CA-46FE-B63D-3CE629CAF70C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The pandemic has changed the way we shop. More people buying things online means more people returning things, too. WSJ&#39;s Dalvin Brown explains how some companies are leveraging gig workers to make those returns for you. Photo illustration: David Fang<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>There is also some chatter online that leaving deliveries visible could lead to other issues.</p><p> “The manufacturer&#39;s box doesn&#39;t have anything holding it shut, and isn&#39;t designed to have a shipping label slapped on it,” a user on X, formerly Twitter, <a href="https://twitter.com/orcakeiko/status/1523136883370254336" target="_blank" class="icon none">wrote</a> , attaching a picture of a computer part shipped without an Amazon box.</p><p> “Amazon didn&#39;t put my vacuum in an Amazon box — I&#39;m gonna be PISSED if someone steals my package by the time I get home,” another user <a href="https://twitter.com/THEHOLYKOREN/status/1687558410970017793" target="_blank" class="icon none">posted</a> .</p><p> Amazon Help&#39;s X account responded to both, citing its “Frustration-Free Packaging” that reduces the amount of packaging material. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/55ae24ee-8937-4c05-801e-4c3a26301b59.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The company sees its packaging initiative as a critical evolution after the success of fast-shipping efforts, Lindner said in an interview. Amazon in the past year has doubled down on getting items to customers quickly by overhauling its delivery operations to reduce how far products travel across the US In its new regionalized model, many items stay near one of eight regions, The Wall Street Journal reported <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-overhauls-delivery-network-to-dispatch-packages-faster-more-cheaply-c10be8b9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">earlier this year.</a></p><p> The massive growth in the company&#39;s warehouse network throughout the pandemic—it roughly doubled its US warehouse space in two years—helps, Lindner said. The less an item has to travel, the easier it is to move without extra packaging. Amazon has cut the distance items travel from fulfillment centers to customers 15%, and decreased “touches,” or how often a package is handled, 12%.</p><p> Amazon tests packages to be eligible to ship without a container, and it says that the system has improved through the use of artificial intelligence. The company performs up to 19 different tests at a facility near its Seattle headquarters that include compressing items, vibrations and drops from different angles.</p><p> One item the company put through its system was a package of screwdrivers. The screwdrivers were originally packaged using soft plastic that made it hazardous to ship without extra protection. Amazon helped the vendor, which it declined to name, design a new, six-sided container that would require no extra packaging.</p><p> Then the company used AI to identify other vendors with similar screwdrivers and shared the new container design with them. The company reduced the size of the package by more than half to about 125 cubic inches, making it less expensive to ship. For 100,000 of the screwdriver packages shipped across a 12-month span, the cost savings through an incentives program tied to the initiative would total about $34,000, Amazon said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=C0596D80-1788-478F-AA8C-D31D0091F4BF" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Incline Impact Test System at Amazon&#39;s testing facility simulates inclined or horizontal impact during loading of items over 100 pounds. VIDEO: Kholood Eid for The Wall Street Journal<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“There&#39;s a lot of stuff that we can do on the packaging design for things you never would have expected were even possible,” such as wine glasses, Lindner said. Amazon hasn&#39;t been able to yet figure out how to eliminate extra packaging for some fragile items such as vinyl records.</p><p> Brita, a seller of filtered water pitchers owned by Clorox, changed its packaging to be eligible for Amazon&#39;s program. The company began with its 6- and 10-cup pitchers.</p><p> Brita&#39;s designs for physical stores and e-commerce are different, said Kirstin Ganz, the company&#39;s brand director. To change its packaging for e-commerce, the challenge is to maintain the allure of unboxing without compromising the structure of the box. Brita&#39;s change included making its box open like a gift box to keep that unboxing experience a customer would have otherwise had with tearing open an Amazon box.</p><p> “Finding an e-commerce solution that delivers that sustainability, that safe shipping and that great unboxing experience is complex to achieve,” Ganz said. “It took us some time to get there.”</p><p> Amazon said it made its packaging changes in part because of feedback from customer surveys. The company in recent years has seen a decline in customer satisfaction on product quality and shopping experience, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazons-customer-satisfaction-slips-with-shoppers-11668986981?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the Journal reported last year.</a></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Lindsey Choo contributed to this article. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832946?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> If Amazon successfully delivers more items in just the manufacturer&#39;s packaging, there will be fewer loads with its signature brown boxes like this one that a delivery worker pulls in New York City.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Sebastian Herrera at <a href="mailto:sebastian.herrera@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sebastian.herrera@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135<author><![CDATA[Sebastian Herrera]]></author><category> wsjexchange</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>wsjcorp</category><category>零售批发</category><category>伊泰林</category><category>E-commerce</category><category> Online Service Providers</category><category> Retail</category><category>技术</category><category>Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Products/Services</category><category> Product/Service Disruptions</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Amazon.com</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category> products</category><category> services</category><category> product</category><category> service disruptions</category><category> retail</category><category>批发的</category><category>电子邮寄</category><category>e-commerce</category><category> online service providers</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Wildfires Leave at Least 55 Dead on Hawaii’s Maui]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>飓风引发的大火摧毁了历史名镇拉海纳<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1E4C7220-8609-4F03-A17C-70F3E330A2CD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Satellite images showed the scale of destruction in the popular tourist town of Lahaina, Hawaii. Photo: Patrick T. Fallon/AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alicia-caldwell" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alicia A. Caldwell</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/suryatapa-bhattacharya" itemprop="url" rel="author">Suryatapa Bhattacharya</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/christine-mai-duc" itemprop="url" rel="author">Christine Mai-Duc</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 11, 2023 4:28 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> MAUI, Hawaii—Travis Miller was pulling into a grocery store in the town of Lahaina on Tuesday when a gust knocked over power lines and toppled trees onto parked cars. Soon he saw smoke and people running down the street, including a woman with burns on her feet, begging for help.</p><p> After dropping her off at an aid center, he rushed to his nearby home, where he heard propane tanks exploding and saw a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-maui-wildfires-hawaii-devastating-84651f12?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fast-moving blaze</a> approaching.</p><p> “I did not know a fire could be that big,” said the 37-year-old photographer, whose home burned down. “It was just tornadoes of fire going up in the air.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833903?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Water is dropped by helicopter on wildfires tearing through the Hawaiian island of Maui.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: US ARMY NATIONAL GUARD/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> At least 55 people have been killed by the wildfire that destroyed much of Lahaina, the historic former capital of the Hawaiian Kingdom and a popular tourist destination, officials said.</p><p> That number is expected to rise in the coming days. Officials said they don&#39;t know how many people are missing, but it could be around 1,000. Search-and-rescue efforts are under way.</p><p> The Lahaina blaze is one of three that have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-wildfires-maui-big-island-lahaina-hurricane-dora-evacuations-800bf315?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">torn through Maui</a> this week, fueled by powerful winds caused by Hurricane Dora spinning hundreds of miles away. None of the fires were fully contained by late Thursday.</p><p> Gov. Josh Green called it the worst natural disaster in Hawaii history and said it would take years and billions of dollars to rebuild. President Biden has declared a major disaster in the state.</p><p> Videos and images from Lahaina show buildings, palm trees and cars engulfed in flames, while wind-whipped walls of fire and smoke spread. By Thursday, there was little more than smoldering rubble where surf shops, restaurants and homes once stood in the town of 12,000.</p><p> A massive, 150-year-old banyan tree that is a central feature of Lahaina&#39;s downtown was also damaged in the fire, which officials said was 80% contained Thursday afternoon.</p><p> “When you see the full extent of the destruction of Lahaina it will shock you,” Green said at a press conference Thursday.</p><p> He said some 1,000 structures have been destroyed and his administration is looking for 2,000 rooms in hotels and homes to temporarily house displaced people.</p><p> Another fire in the coastal town of Pulehu was 70% contained. A third fire, in the island&#39;s rural Upcountry, was still being assessed, but authorities said earlier that at least 1,000 acres burned in the area, home to Haleakala National Park. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833904?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A 150-year-old banyan tree was damaged in the fire that devastated downtown Lahaina.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: MARCO GARCIA/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Officials haven&#39;t determined the causes of the Maui wildfires, which started Tuesday and Wednesday.</p><p> They said they hadn&#39;t anticipated how quickly the Lahaina fire ended up moving into populated areas and that the rapid damage it caused made communications among emergency responders impossible at times.</p><p> Local residents said the Lahaina blaze didn&#39;t seem serious at first, until winds as fast as 60 miles an hour spread it out of control.</p><p> “Within just two or three hours, the majority of the town was gone,” said Richard Coennen, a 37-year-old project manager for a construction company.</p><p> Bosco Bae, a 39 year-old art gallery employee, said, “It was very apocalyptic…I couldn&#39;t see a thing, but it was like raining fire, embers raining down.”</p><p> Residents reported running into the water to escape the flames. The Coast Guard said it rescued 14 people from the ocean.</p><p> Eddy Garcia was working on his farm outside Lahaina when powerful winds started sweeping through his property, eventually causing the first tornado he had ever seen.</p><p> “It 100% devastated all my structures—lifted up things and threw them in the air, and busted all the power lines in this small area,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1090" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/b962de2e-47c2-43e9-bada-09e646fc6ee9-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> When he ventured into the town of Lahaina, he saw devastation everywhere.</p><p> “Everything is burnt to concrete frames. There&#39;s nothing left,” said Garcia. “If their house is gone, it&#39;s gone. Like all the way to the frame. There&#39;s nothing for them to collect.”</p><p> Garcia said he plans to kill a few pigs from his farm to help feed the community in the coming days.</p><p> Some 11,000 people were without power across the western of Maui, according to the Federal Emergency Management Agency, and cellphone and landline service had been knocked out.</p><p> The fires will likely be devastating to Maui&#39;s tourism industry. Nearly 1.5 million people visited the island in the first half of the year, up 5.7% from the same period in 2022, according to the state&#39;s Department of Business, Economic Development and Tourism.同期游客总支出为 34.7 亿美元，比去年增长约 25%。</p><p> AccuWeather estimated that the wildfires will cause $8 billion to $10 billion of damage and economic loss to Hawaii. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833907?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Burned-out cars were part of the trail of destruction left by the wildfire in Lahaina, Hawaii.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tiffany Kidder Winn/AP </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833905?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Residents carrying their belongings in suitcases after a wildfire swept through Lahaina.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ku&#39;u Kauanoe/Civil Beat/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> FEMA 表示，截至周四上午，毛伊岛的 6 个避难所已容纳 2000 多人。</p><p> Cecilia Paredes-Sunshine was on the second week of a vacation with her husband and three children in Maui when she saw billowing smoke and flames from her hotel located just north of Lahaina.</p><p> “You could see the black smoke all night,” the 47 year-old from Newport Beach, Calif., said.</p><p> With many roads closed, her family made their way through long, twisty back roads lined by burned trees to the town of Kahului. All of the local hotels were booked, so they rented a pair of sport-utility vehicles with roof-mounted tents and spent the night Wednesday in the parking lot of Maui High School, a shelter where other evacuees slept on mats on the floor. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="640" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/0e1c440f-9468-472b-9b4b-a40a24b48f11-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> President Biden addressed the disaster before a planned speech on veterans&#39; healthcare in Utah on Thursday. “Our prayers are with the people of Hawaii, but not just our prayers,” he said. “Every asset we have will be available.”</p><p>今年夏天，野火和其他形式的极端天气席卷了世界多个地区。大火席卷了希腊、葡萄牙和加拿大，而中国则面临着严重的洪水和灼热的热浪。 July was the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">world&#39;s hottest month on record</a> .</p><p> “Climate change is here and it&#39;s affecting the islands and I think that&#39;s what you&#39;re seeing in this fire,” Green, the Hawaii governor, said.</p><p> Lahaina, which according to the local travel industry attracts about 80% of the tourists who visit Maui each year, is on the National Register of Historic Places. Hailama Farden, former president of the Hawaiian Historical Society, rode a tram through Lahaina as a child and learned about the groves of coconut trees, as well as the churches, temples and graveyards.</p><p> He had planned to take his 7-year-old daughter to Lahaina this weekend to show her the buildings where her great-grandparents and other relatives lived.</p><p> “I live vicariously through the stories of my grandfolks,” said Farden, 52. “I mourn the footsteps of my elders. I mourn for the culture that was.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833899?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An aerial image taken Thursday shows homes and other buildings burned to the ground in Lahaina, Hawaii.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：帕特里克·T.法伦/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine">—Jennifer Calfas, Erin Ailworth, Allison Pohle, Ethan M. Steinberg, Michael Wright and Annie Linskey contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Alicia A. Caldwell at <a href="mailto:alicia.caldwell@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alicia.caldwell@wsj.com</a> , Suryatapa Bhattacharya at <a href="mailto:Suryatapa.Bhattacharya@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Suryatapa.Bhattacharya@wsj.com</a> and Christine Mai-Duc at <a href="mailto:christine.maiduc@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">christine.maiduc@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 08:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7<author><![CDATA[Alicia A. CaldwellSuryatapa BhattacharyaChristine Mai-Duc]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category>野火</category><category>wsj-usnews</category><category>野火</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>飓风/台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>Natural Disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>飓风</category><category>台风</category><category>storms</category><category> natural disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[AI Mania Triggers Dot-Com Bubble Flashbacks]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nvidia shares have nearly tripled this year. Investors question whether the stock can live up to the hype. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831662/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal <span>Illustration by Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118695"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118695"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-wallerstein" itemprop="url" rel="author">Eric Wallerstein</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 11, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/artificial-intelligence-stocks-dot-com-bubble-fears-7848d402"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The dot-com bubble taught investors to be wary of stock-market rallies powered by a technological boom—that is, until generative artificial intelligence sent tech stocks soaring this year.</p><p> Shares of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">Nvidia</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the graphics-chip maker at the heart of the frenzy, have nearly tripled in 2023, while the Nasdaq-100 has climbed 38% and the S&amp;P 500 has gained 16%.</p><p> For some investors, the surge in Nvidia—now the fifth-largest US company by market value—is difficult to chalk up to anything but <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/grantham-warns-ai-boom-wont-prevent-market-bubble-from-bursting-fd7f5a98?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">speculative mania</a> . Its weighting in the benchmark stock indexes means everyday investors are at the whims of its trajectory, whether they believe in AI&#39;s potential or not. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834067?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “There&#39;s a huge boom in AI—some people are scrambling to get exposure at any cost, while others are sounding the alarm that this will end in tears,” said Kai Wu, founder and chief investment officer of Sparkline Capital. “Investors can benefit from innovation-led growth, but must be wary of overpaying for it.”</p><p> Nvidia is the primary producer of semiconductors backing artificial-intelligence systems. The company forecast a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nvidia-nvda-q1-earnings-report-2024-132e3559?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">record $11 billion in sales</a> for the recently ended quarter when it reported results in May, catching analysts off guard with the projected surge in customer demand.</p><p> “That&#39;s when the excitement around AI really ramped up,” said Ryan McCormack, an Invesco senior exchange-traded fund strategist.</p><p> The hype has driven companies such as Meta Platforms and Amazon.com that have been building out AI capabilities, he said. Shares of the tech giants are up 154% and 65% in 2023, respectively. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">Microsoft</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> which has climbed 35%, has poured <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-says-it-plans-multibillion-dollar-investment-in-openai-11674483180?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">billions of dollars</a> into OpenAI&#39;s ChatGPT, a chatbot that can answer <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-openai-math-artificial-intelligence-8aba83f0" target="_blank" class="icon none">difficult questions in seconds</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E8DCC2B0-F066-41EA-9053-96EC3A35B05E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fartificial-intelligence-stocks-dot-com-bubble-fears-7848d402&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> WSJ breaks down how Nvidia attained a $1 trillion market cap—and how AI is fueling the company&#39;s rapid growth.插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The furious rally in those stocks, long the market&#39;s biggest drivers, has fanned worries about <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-rally-is-all-about-a-few-star-stocksand-some-investors-are-worried-b64382e2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">market concentration</a> . The 10 biggest stocks in the S&amp;P 500 now comprise more than a third of the market, according to Dow Jones Market Data. They represented 27% of the index at the start of the year and less than a quarter in 2000.</p><p> “The market story that rhymes most with the internet bubble is the concentration of leadership,” said Mike Edwards, deputy chief investment officer of Weiss Multi-Strategy Advisers.</p><p> Nvidia&#39;s second-quarter earnings report, due Aug. 23, will provide insight into whether its inexorable rise is well-rooted in demand for chips, or a product of hype. The stock gained 24% in the trading session after its earnings reported in May, and 14% the day following February&#39;s results. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833832?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Investors are paying up for the shares, betting on a windfall down the line. Nvidia is trading at 41 times its sales from the last 12 months, according to FactSet, compared with 2.4 times sales for the S&amp;P 500. On a forward basis, the stock trades at 20 times its expected sales for the year ahead—double its average over the last decade of 10 times, according to Dow Jones Market Data.</p><p> The nascency of AI programs such as ChatGPT means it is likely too early to determine whether Nvidia can raise revenue in line with the eye-watering valuation investors have slapped on its shares. If the company&#39;s growth isn&#39;t enough to reflect its price, the stock could crater.</p><p> A basket of 43 high-multiple internet stocks—those worth at least $5 billion that traded at 25 times their revenue at the turn of the century—crashed 80% over the next two years, according to Sparkline.</p><p> The companies weren&#39;t duds, either. Their sales grew 10-fold in the ensuing two decades. But investors were badly bruised from the bust: The shares returned an average of 16% in that time span. The S&amp;P 500 returned 284%.</p><p> The basket included Amazon and Microsoft, both darlings of today&#39;s market, along with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSCO" class="">Cisco Systems</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> then one of the largest companies in the Nasdaq-100. The networking- equipment maker traded as high as 38 times its sales in early 2000. Cisco has returned 43% since the start of the century—it is down 0.4% when excluding dividends.</p><p> “Valuations matter,” said Wu. “Investing in stocks exposed to rapidly growing technologies only works if the growth is not already priced in. Unfortunately, in periods of euphoria, the market has a tendency not only to price in potential growth, but to greatly overextrapolate it.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Do you think the AI boom is a bubble?为什么或者为什么不？ Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> One reason why this rally might lack the boom-and-bust nature of the dot-com bubble: The beneficiaries of artificial intelligence were the stocks already shining this year. Investors were flocking to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">big tech</a> in the first quarter, seeking shelter in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-flock-to-safety-plays-but-stock-fomo-lingers-f821acbd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">strong balance sheet</a> s and cash flows.</p><p> Tech companies are also benefiting from the expected end of the Federal Reserve&#39;s interest-rate campaign and resilient consumer spending. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-bull-market-is-just-getting-started-traders-bet-bd9fd930?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Cyclical sectors</a> of the broader market have begun to catch up now that recession fears are fading.</p><p> “It&#39;s not like 1999 when investors were racing to hot IPOs for companies that had no chance of making money,” said Edwards. “Today&#39;s winners are disciplined, enormous companies that have moats in place and data sets to exploit.”</p><p> Write to Eric Wallerstein at <a href="mailto:eric.wallerstein@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.wallerstein@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d90969df-db3f-4890-9f4e-2892f502493a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/artificial-intelligence-stocks-dot-com-bubble-fears-7848d402</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/artificial-intelligence-stocks-dot-com-bubble-fears-7848d402<author><![CDATA[Eric Wallerstein]]></author><category> wsjfinance</category><category> wsjfinance-markets</category><category> Computers/Consumer Electronics</category><category> Artificial Intelligence Technologies</category><category> Semiconductors</category><category> Computing</category><category> Computer Hardware</category><category> Industrial Electronics</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category> Integrated Circuits</category><category>技术</category><category>Graphics Processing Units</category><category> Financial Performance</category><category> Share Price Movement/Disruptions</category><category> Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Equity Markets</category><category> Commodity/Financial Market News</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> C&amp;E Industry News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>英伟达</category><category>NVDA</category><category> financial performance</category><category> share price movement</category><category> disruptions</category><category> corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category> equity markets</category><category> commodity</category><category> financial market news</category><category> content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> c&amp;e industry news filter</category><category> computers</category><category> consumer electronics</category><category> artificial intelligence technologies</category><category> semiconductors</category><category> computing</category><category> computer hardware</category><category> industrial electronics</category><category> industrial goods</category><category> integrated circuits</category><category>技术</category><category>graphics processing units </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cruise, Waymo Get Approval to Expand Driverless Vehicles in San Francisco]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> California regulator votes to allow autonomous car companies to add cars and charge for rides <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127560"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832203?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Waymo said it would begin charging fares for trips in its self-driving cars in San Francisco in coming weeks.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Poppy Lynch for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127560"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lindsey-choo" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lindsey Choo</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 10, 2023 11:13 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cruise-waymo-get-approval-to-expand-driverless-vehicles-in-san-francisco-923fe89d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Self-driving car companies Cruise and Waymo can expand in San Francisco.</p><p> The California Public Utilities Commission, which regulates passenger transportation, voted on Thursday to allow Cruise, majority owned by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GM" class="">General Motors</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> and Waymo, part of Google parent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="">Alphabet</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> to deploy more vehicles in the city and to start charging for rides at all times.</p><p> The result, after a vote that had been delayed twice, signifies a big win for the self-driving car companies in their quest to expand statewide and to other cities across the US</p><p> San Francisco has played host to thousands of self-driving car test miles, and some residents are regular users. Now the companies want to offer ride-hailing businesses that can compete with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LYFT" class="company-name">Lyft</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> Residents <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-most-tech-forward-city-has-doubts-about-self-driving-cars-d6b098e0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have expressed concerns</a> about their deployment. Some first responders say they get in the way, and pedestrians have filled social media with reports of the cars&#39; antics.</p><p> “We do expect the AV companies to engage with first responders, with law enforcement, with city officials, and we do expect actions to address concerns. In the meantime, the resolutions before us do meet our requirements,” said Alice Reynolds, president of the commission. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F0A447AB-6ED9-4EB3-B7A8-1EE00682BB50&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcruise-waymo-get-approval-to-expand-driverless-vehicles-in-san-francisco-923fe89d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Waymo is operating fully driverless robotaxis in Chandler, Ariz., and recently took a step toward offering the same to riders in San Francisco. It is a test that could provide a roadmap for Waymo&#39;s expansion and help the Google sister company build a revenue-generating business. Photo: Karl Mollohan<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The commission voted 3 to 1 to approve the companies&#39; proposals. Commissioner Genevieve Shiroma rejected them after saying a vote was premature. She pointed out that Cruise and Waymo hadn&#39;t provided the number of vehicles they planned to deploy if the resolutions were approved.</p><p> Waymo said Thursday after the vote it will begin charging fares for rider-only trips in the city in coming weeks and will be gradually inviting more people on the wait list for the app to ride. Cruise didn&#39;t immediately respond to a request for comment. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832202?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Cruise self-driving car stopped at an intersection in San Francisco last month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Poppy Lynch for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Before the vote, dozens of people spent several hours making public comments for and against the companies&#39; proposals. Some urged the commission to reject them, citing concerns over the readiness of the technology, disability accessibility and the threat to human jobs.</p><p> Others encouraged the commission to embrace technology that could eliminate human error and improve safety and disability accessibility. Some in favor of the proposals identified themselves as testers and partners associated with Cruise and Waymo.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Before the vote, Commissioner Darcie Houck also asked commission staff to report back on safety incidents and reports within three months if the companies&#39; proposals were accepted.</p><p> Cruise currently offers paid rides at night in San Francisco, while people have been riding in Waymo cars free of charge as the company sought the state&#39;s permission to offer paid rides. Both apps have waiting lists.</p><p> In May, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/california-regulator-looking-into-anonymous-letter-alleging-cruises-robotaxi-service-wasnt-ready-for-launch-11657811102?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">San Francisco city officials</a> sent a letter to the state expressing concerns about the proposed expansion in the city. City officials said the number of reported incidents involving Cruise and Waymo vehicles has tripled in recent months.</p><p> Cruise and Waymo both previously told The Wall Street Journal that their cars haven&#39;t caused any traffic fatalities. In their first million miles driven, Waymo said its self-driving vehicles in fully autonomous mode didn&#39;t cause any collisions with human drivers.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Would you ride in a self-driving car? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> As both companies plan their expansions, they face pressure from not only city officials but also their shareholders. So far, the businesses have produced minimal revenue. GM reported $102 million in sales and $3.3 billion in costs and expenses related to Cruise last year. Alphabet <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/activist-investor-calls-on-google-parent-alphabet-to-slash-costs-11668528859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was asked by shareholders</a> last November to cut their losses on long-term bets like Waymo.</p><p> While the companies have stated their plans to expand nationwide, they still face a long path ahead to persuade consumers to try the service. A 2022 poll by consumer-intelligence firm JD Power showed that most consumers are comfortable with driver-assist features, but only 12% indicated they are comfortable with full self-driving features.</p><p> Write to Lindsey Choo at <a href="mailto:lindsey.choo@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">lindsey.choo@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 03:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cruise-waymo-get-approval-to-expand-driverless-vehicles-in-san-francisco-923fe89d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cruise-waymo-get-approval-to-expand-driverless-vehicles-in-san-francisco-923fe89d<author><![CDATA[Lindsey Choo]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category> Internet Search Engines</category><category> Autonomous Driving Technologies</category><category> Automotive</category><category> Online Service Providers</category><category>技术</category><category>Regulation/Government Policy</category><category> Corporate/Industrial News</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Cruises</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category>旅行</category><category>Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Industry News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Alphabet Cl A</category><category> GOOGL</category><category> General Motors</category><category> GM</category><category>规定</category><category>government policy</category><category> corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>cruises</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>travel</category><category> content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e industry news filter</category><category> internet search engines</category><category> autonomous driving technologies</category><category> automotive</category><category> online service providers</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A New Omicron Subvariant, Dubbed ‘Eris,’ Heralds Covid-19’s Resurgence]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>我们对美国最常见的亚变体 EG.5 的了解<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833284?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">曼哈顿的一个弹出式 Covid-19 测试帐篷。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的加比·琼斯</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/brianna-abbott" itemprop="url" rel="author">布莱恩娜·阿博特</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-kamp" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·坎普</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-s-hopkins" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·S·霍普金斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 3:18（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>现在还不要指望 Covid-19 被排除在外。</p><p>随着 Omicron 变种的另一个分支势头强劲，美国的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Covid-19 感染人数</a>正在上升——在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-influenza-covid-19-tripledemic-this-winter-11667560508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">呼吸道疾病</a>通常会激增的秋季之前。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-do-we-actually-know-about-covid-19-not-enough-ec1dcafe?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">该病毒的持续进化</a>提醒人们，尽管这种疾病的破坏性远不如以前，但 Covid-19 仍然对许多人来说是一个麻烦，对一些人来说仍然是一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/long-covid-symptoms-recovery-not-over-2e535790?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">严重的风险</a>。废水中病毒浓度的不断上升和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/face-mask-mandates-fall-away-among-many-hospitals-doctors-6ecaa3e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">医院感染的</a>增加表明，Covid-19 仍然难以预测。</p><p>这种名为 EG.5 的新亚变体是另一个名为 XBB.1.9.2 的变体的后代，据世界卫生组织称，自 8 月 7 日以来，至少有 51 个国家报告了该变体，该组织将 EG.5 归类为本周感兴趣的一个变体。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833823?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> X（以前称为 Twitter）上的一些科学家将其非正式地称为“Eris”。世界卫生组织表示，与其他 Omicron 亚变体一样，EG.5 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/omicrons-trajectory-shows-challenge-of-maintaining-immune-defenses-11651829400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">具有免疫逃逸特性</a>，但没有迹象表明它更严重。</p><p>据美国疾病控制与预防中心称，截至 8 月 5 日，EG.5 预计约占美国病例的 17%，使其成为美国最流行的病毒版本。它是由十多个 Omicron 分支组成的动物园之一，估计至少占病例的 1%。</p><p>路易斯安那州卫生官员兼路易斯安那州卫生部医疗主任约瑟夫·坎特博士表示，由于没有足够的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cdc-director-rochelle-walensky-politicization-science-9c291c7e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">检测和测序数据</a>，疾病预防控制中心无法再对美国每个地区进行变异预测。</p><p> “我们预计 EG.5 将继续发挥重要作用，”坎特说。</p><p>卫生官员、疫苗制造商和医生正在为秋季疫苗接种活动做准备，这次活动将与之前的活动有所不同：疫苗将通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-plans-for-end-of-covid-19-shot-treatment-coverage-11660838418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">商业市场</a>而不是政府购买分发给药房和医生办公室。这些疫苗针对的是最近占主导地位的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-covid-shots-in-the-u-s-will-target-omicron-offshoot-xbb-1-5-35e212a0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">XBB.1.5 菌株，</a>符合美国食品和药物管理局今年早些时候制定的指示。</p><p>坎特说，针对 XBB.1.5 更新的助推器应该保留针对 EG.5 的良好保护，因为 Omicron 子变体是相似的。他说，很难预测这种保护会持续多久。</p><p>辉瑞首席执行官艾伯特·布尔拉 (Albert Bourla) 本月表示，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PFE" class="company-name">辉瑞</a>预计其新疫苗将于本月获得批准，疫苗接种可能于 9 月开始。辉瑞公司发言人表示，预计该增强剂能够对抗 EG.5，因为它是 Omicron 的一个分支，但正在进行实验室测试以确保这一点。辉瑞和合作伙伴<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BNTX" class="company-name">BioNTech</a>在 6 月份的会议上向 FDA 顾问介绍了如何更新疫苗的动物测试。</p><p> FDA 不太可能要求制造商生产针对 EG.5 的疫苗，因为供应无法及时准备好以供秋季活动使用。辉瑞和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MRNA" class="company-name">Moderna</a>至少需要三个月的时间才能针对 Covid-19 进行 mRNA 注射。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>发言人表示，Moderna 的更新疫苗供应充足，正在等待 FDA 批准分配剂量。他说，初步测试表明该镜头对 EG.5 有效，更多测试正在进行中。</p><p>一位发言人表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVAX" class="">Novavax</a>的 Covid-19 疫苗使用了不同的技术，该公司正在向监管机构提交数据以授权其加强剂，并预计在 9 月份获得许可并发货。</p><p>是否立即接受加强注射或等待新的加强注射<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/think-you-never-got-covid-19-thank-your-genes-d61c7507?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取决于某人的健康状况和风险</a>， <strong>&nbsp;</strong>威尔康奈尔医学院微生物学和免疫学教授约翰摩尔博士说。他说，患有已有疾病或免疫系统受损的人以及未接种疫苗的人仍然面临高风险。</p><p> “如果您和您的医生认为您现在需要加强针，请立即购买，”摩尔说。 “这非常有个性。没有一个简单的桶可以容纳每个美国人。”</p><p>去年，RSV 早期严重激增以及流感导致<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-hospitalizations-babies-young-children-11668080478?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">儿科医院不堪重负</a>，卫生官员正在为其他呼吸道感染的增加做好准备。 FDA 已批准首款<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-pfizer-rsv-vaccine-rolls-out-into-headwinds-of-hesitancy-74c8aece?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于 60 岁及以上成年人的</a>RSV 疫苗以及一种<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fda-approves-first-rsv-drug-to-protect-all-infants-from-virus-52907caf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于保护婴儿的新药</a>。</p><p> “我们正在进入一个我们并不真正知道这些病毒将如何相互作用的季节，”康涅狄格州公共卫生部专员马尼沙·朱萨尼博士说。</p><p>美国不再像以前那样密切跟踪 Covid-19 感染和住院情况。长期以来，感染情况一直难以记录，因为人们不再在向州卫生当局提供数据的设施中接受检测。医院还取消了对所有患者的常规检测。</p><p>几周来，医院内的 Covid-19 病例一直呈上升趋势。 CDC 表示，截至 7 月底的最新一周内，有 9,056 人因 Covid-19 入院，增长了 12.5%。许多患者因其他原因住院，而不是因为感染，但医院的阳性检测可以反映出社区感染流行率的增加。</p><p> Covid-19 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-million-deaths-the-hole-the-pandemic-made-in-u-s-society-11643662159?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">每天都会导致新的死亡病例</a>，尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-u-s-covid-19-death-toll-is-still-rising-93b2b12a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">远未达到大流行初期的峰值</a>。最近的死亡证明数据显示，美国平均每天有不到 100 例 Covid-19 死亡病例。 2021 年 1 月，一周内每天死亡人数达到历史最高值约 3,700 人。</p><p>写信给 Brianna Abbott（ <a href="mailto:brianna.abbott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">brianna.abbott@wsj.com</a> ）、Jon Kamp（ <a href="mailto:Jon.Kamp@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jon.Kamp@wsj.com</a> ）和 Jared S. Hopkins（ <a href="mailto:jared.hopkins@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.hopkins@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 19:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260<author><![CDATA[Brianna AbbottJon KampJared S. Hopkins]]></author><category>华尔街日报健康</category><category>药品</category><category>疫苗</category><category>纺织品</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>服装/纺织品</category><category>消费品</category><category>特殊药物/药物</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category>健康</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>Medical Conditions</category><category> Outbreaks/Epidemics</category><category> Novel Coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>Medical Treatments/Procedures</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>莫德纳</category><category>信使核糖核酸</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category> health</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>medical conditions</category><category>爆发</category><category>epidemics</category><category> novel coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>medical treatments</category><category> procedures</category><category>药品</category><category>疫苗</category><category>纺织品</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>衣服</category><category>消费品</category><category>专门药物</category><category>medications </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A 2-Hour Workout in 20 Minutes? My Week Testing a High-Tech Fitness Suit]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The Katalyst training suit promises to use muscle-stimulating electrodes to supercharge guided workouts. One skeptical writer zipped herself in for a week. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831818/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="SHOCK IT TO ME The Katalyst training suit is expensive, but doctors and trainers say it uses relatively standard technology." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> SHOCK IT TO ME The Katalyst training suit is expensive, but doctors and trainers say it uses relatively standard technology. Katalyst <span>Katalyst</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101409"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101409"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Perri Ormont Blumberg</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 10, 2023 3:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-2-hour-workout-in-20-minutes-my-week-testing-a-high-tech-fitness-suit-e3d09134"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> <strong>SUMMER&#39;S HERE</strong> and the livin&#39; is lazy. So when I learned of a wearable suit that stimulates your muscles while you <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-home-gym-equipment-watches-you-work-out-thats-mostly-a-good-thing-6b5471cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">exercise with virtual coaches</a> and promises to make a 20-minute workout as effective as a two-hour one, I was eager to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/therabody-recoveryair-jetboots-review-11650545039?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">try it out</a> .</p><p> I&#39;ve never seen anything like the tangle of a vest, belt, shorts, arm bands and electrodes that is the <a href="https://katalyst.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Katalyst Training System</a> ($2,499, annual membership from $49/month), but the technology it employs is actually somewhat conventional. It works via electrical muscle stimulation (EMS), eliciting “muscle contraction using electrical impulses,” said Sabrena Jo, senior director of science and research for American Council on Exercise (ACE).</p><p> Initially conceived to rehabilitate injured muscles, EMS devices are gaining popularity as a training timesaver. Dr. Gabrielle Lyon, a doctor of functional medicine in New York, says EMS training can activate nearly twice as much muscle fiber as traditional strength training. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823768?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> PUNCH UP Dr. Gabrielle Lyon, a doctor of functional medicine in New York, says EMS training can activate nearly twice as much muscle fiber as traditional strength training.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Katalyst</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Here, notes from my week zipping myself into the (mercifully machine-washable) skin suit. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <strong>DAY 1</strong></p><p> The hardest part of today&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fitness-ring-reviews-can-they-actually-pass-as-jewelry-80815343?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">workout</a> ? The 30 minutes of huffing it took to strap into my suit. Once I paired it with its app, I selected my desired impulse intensity. Katalyst offers workouts organized in broad categories like “strength,” “power,” “cardio” and “recovery.” I opted for a 20-minute general strength workout and appreciated that the prescribed circuit of lunges, squats and arm raises didn&#39;t strain my joints. The pulses felt like a tingly pinch, no pain at all. I was less thrilled by the need to pause mid-squat to tighten the suit&#39;s straps. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <strong>DAY 2</strong></p><p> It only took 15 minutes to shimmy into the suit this time. I enjoyed the restorative yoga in the 15-minute recovery video I tried, but it&#39;s hard to feel truly zen with cords hanging off your body. At times, the bottom of the vest dug into my stomach. Still, I slept wonderfully that night. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <strong>DAY 3</strong></p><p> Getting myself into the Katalyst remained a time suck, but I hardly noticed. I was eager to get back to a more action-packed program. By the end, I&#39;m dripping in sweat, with a heart rate throbbing in what my smartwatch says is the “ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-thought-i-was-a-terrible-runner-this-free-app-changed-my-mind-11675868401?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cardio zone</a> .” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <strong>DAY 4</strong></p><p> Katalyst says not to use it too many days in a row, so…rest day! </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <strong>DAY 5</strong></p><p> A 20-minute interval cardio workout took me to Sweat City. I have gotten much better at heeding the instructor&#39;s commands with grace, even within constricting get-up. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <strong>DAY 6</strong></p><p> I felt great but still took the suggested break from the suit. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <strong>DAY 7</strong></p><p> For my final workout, I settled on a 10-minute low-impact cardio.</p><p> Ultimately, I think the system delivers on its promise to provide effective, fun workouts, but I am not convinced you can get all the benefits of a two-hour sweat in a short session. As I wrapped up, my mind was on pizza. Now that I don&#39;t have to worry about zipping myself into a skintight contraption, I could actually eat some.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Would you try EMS training?为什么或者为什么不？ Join the conversation below.</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
